- [ ] HTML 
HTML (HyperText Markup Language) 
is the standard language used to create and structure web pages. It tells the browser what content to display and how it is organized (text, images, links, forms, etc.).

HTML is not a programming language — it is a markup language.
HTML is not a programming language because it cannot perform logic or calculations.
   A programming language can:
* Make decisions (if–else)
* Perform calculations
* Use loops
* Manipulate data dynamically
HTML cannot do any of these. It only describes what content should appear on a web page.

HTML is a markup language because it uses tags to mark up content.
These tags tell the browser:
* What type of content it is
* How it should be displayed or structured


Structure of an HTML Document


<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>My First Web Page</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Hello World</h1>
    <p>This is my first HTML page.</p>
</body>
</html>
Explanation of Tags
* <!DOCTYPE html> → Declares that the document uses HTML5
* <html> → Root element that contains the entire HTML document
* <head> → Contains metadata such as title, styles, links, and scripts (This content is not visible on the web page)
* <title> → Displays the page title on the browser tab
* <body> → Contains all the visible content of the web page (text, images, links, forms, etc.)

HTML Attributes

Attributes give extra information to elements.
FOR EXAMPLE:

<img src="photo.jpg" alt="My Photo" width="200">
* src → Image path
* alt → Alternative text
* width → Image size

Lists in HTML
                           Ordered List.  
                                     Used when the order of items is important.

                           Unordered List
                                     Used when the order of items is not important.

 
Forms in HTML
