- [ ] Frontend 
Frontend (Client-Side Development)
Definition:
Frontend is the part of a website or web application that users see and interact with directly. It is built using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, along with frameworks and libraries.
Purpose:
* Display content to users
* Make the website visually appealing
* Handle user interactions
* Provide a smooth user experience (UX)

What Frontend Developers Do:
* Create responsive pages (work on mobile, tablet, desktop)
* Add animations and transitions
* Handle form validation (login/signup)
* Fetch and display data from APIs
* Ensure accessibility and SEO

(SEO is the process of optimizing a website so that it appears higher in search engine results (like Google, Bing) for relevant keywords.)

***************************************************************************************************************************

Backend
Backend (Server-Side Development)
Definition:
Backend is the part of a web application that runs on the server and handles data processing, storage, security, and business logic. It works behind the scenes and is not directly visible to users.

Purpose:
* Store and manage data (databases)
* Authenticate users (login/signup)
* Handle business logic (calculations, workflows)
* Communicate with frontend via APIs
* Ensure security and permissions

What Backend Developers Do:
* Create APIs for frontend to fetch or send data
* Connect websites to databases
* Validate and process user input securely
* Implement authentication and authorization
* Handle file uploads, payments, notifications

Example:
In Amazon:
* User adds items to the cart → Backend updates the cart in the database
* User places an order → Backend processes payment, updates inventory
* Order confirmation → Backend sends data to frontend
 
